0-C  FORCE INTERPRETER PATH AT COMPILE TIME  (Category 1 fix)
     SOURCE: Audit Sections 2.3-ADDENDUM (2.3-F), Phase 21
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
This is the #1 crash risk. Do it before any linking.

WHY: The nVif micro-JIT (dVifUnpack) generates ARM64 NEON machine code at
runtime. On iOS, the init path via iOSVMManager does not go through
VMManager::StartVM(), so nVif[idx].vifBlocks.m_bucket is never initialized.
The first VIF UNPACK command from any game causes immediate SIGSEGV at
Vif_HashBucket.h:68. Setting newVifDynaRec = 0 routes all VIF unpack
operations through the pure C++ interpreter path.
Performance cost: 5–15% on bandwidth-heavy games — acceptable for bringup.

Open pcsx2/Vif_Dynarec.h and replace:
  static constexpr bool newVifDynaRec = 1;

With:
  #if defined(__APPLE__) && defined(TARGET_OS_IOS) && TARGET_OS_IOS
  static constexpr bool newVifDynaRec = 0;  // iOS: no JIT, interpreter path
  #else
  static constexpr bool newVifDynaRec = 1;
  #endif

In CMakeLists.txt, add to iOS target compile definitions:
  target_compile_definitions(BionicSX2 PRIVATE
    PCSX2_TARGET_IOS=1
  )

Also add belt-and-suspenders CMake-level define:
  add_compile_definitions(TARGET_OS_IOS=1)
  add_compile_definitions(VIXL_CODE_BUFFER_MMAP=0)

Verify with:
  grep -n "PCSX2_TARGET_IOS" CMakeLists.txt Vif_Dynarec.h
